The independent educational centres in Scotland have a career of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the examinations that are reinforced by individual and collective success in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Independent Colleges Council (SCIS, for their English stamps), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted study plan, modern languages remain a popular and desired assignment in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message reaches his head.
If you speak your language, it will reach your heart."
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries, you cannot depend solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's examinations, we can see that the languages are at the highest of the classification tables, with higher approval rates in independent colleges.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest score.
The data collected from the 74 centres forming part of the SCIS showed that 72% of the students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of the German students, 69% of the French students and 63% of the Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that independent colleges in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM assignments (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent colleges and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the United Kingdom Employment and Competence Commission revealed that, for reasons given by entrepreneurs about the difficulties encountered in covering jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race that someone chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last all your life.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to advance automatically to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language as well as to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If you know a number of languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each college will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the most important languages for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent colleges you can always choose from several languages provided by teaching staff specialized in this matter.
Independent education centres in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the necessary skills to succeed, whatever the future for them.
At this point, it is undisputed that, in a global business environment, languages remain vital for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competence for international communication".
Independent colleges will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It needs to be done.
