Federal prosecutors exceptionally seek the death penalty for suspected terrorist attack in New York
The federal prosecutors in New York are looking for the capital punishment for Sayfullo Saipov, the suspect of the terrorist attack in New York City that killed eight people, an exceptional punishment that has not been executed in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
Saipov, 30-year-old, allegedly used a Home Depot rental truck to carry out a bike attack last October on the West Side highway of Bajo Manhattan, striking down the pedestrians and cyclists he was on his way.
In order to justify a death penalty, the prosecutors must prove that Saipov "intendedly" killed the eight victims and "intendedly" caused serious bodily injuries, according to the notice of the intention to request a death penalty, presented in the South District of New York.
The two charges entail a possible death penalty, according to the court document.
Several weeks after the attack, a large federal jury filed a charge to Saipov with 22 charges including eight counts of murder with organized crime, which are often used by federal prosecutors in these cases, and a charge of violence and destruction of motorized vehicles.
The attack required "substantial planning and premeditation", according to prosecutors, who described the way in which Saipov carried it out as "atrocious, cruel and devious".
"Sayfull Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco", specified in the notice of intent.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It's been a decade since the South District of New York processed a death penalty case.
The accused, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug dealers, but was finally sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time a death penalty was executed in a New York federal case was in Julius and Ethel Rosenberg in 1953. This marriage was executed after they were sentenced by conspiracy to spy on the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The two Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on 19 June 1953.
Saipov, an immigrant from Uzbekistan, showed his lack of remorse during the days and months after the attack, according to court documents.
According to the police, he told the investigators that he felt good about what he had done.
According to the charge, Saipov told the authorities that for his attack he was inspired by videos of ISIS on his phone.
She also asked for the ISIS flag to be removed in her hospital room, the police said.
It has been declared not guilty of the 22 charges.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders lawyers representing Saipov, said they are "evidently disappointed" with the decision of the prosecutor.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty rather than accept a declaration of guilt with a sentence of eternal chains without the possibility of release will only prolong the trauma of these events for all those involved," Patton said.
The Saipov defence team had previously requested prosecutors who would not claim the death penalty.
