Update of the red tide: Reduces concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission report shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Bay of Tampa.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately 130 miles along the coast from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Unregular plots can be found about 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in the county of Pasco.
Average concentrations have been reported in the County of Pinellas and on its coast, low and high concentrations in the County of Hillsborough, high-end concentrations in the County of Manatee, high-end concentrations in the County of Sarasota and its coast, low-end concentrations in the County of Charlotte, high-end concentrations in the County of Lee and on its coast, and low concentrations in the County of Collier.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation problems in the county of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation problems in the northwest of Florida during the last week.
